Shell scripting essentials.

A shell script is just a file with shell commands in it. The shell reads it line by line and runs each line exactly as if you had typed it at the prompt. That is the whole idea; everything else is detail.

The first line of any executable script should be the shebang, written as a hash and an exclamation mark followed by the path to the interpreter, for instance pointing at bash. That line tells the system which program should run the rest of the file. Once you have written a script, there are two ways to run it. You can hand the file to bash explicitly, which works even without the shebang or execute permission. Or you can run it as a command in its own right, by giving its path, which needs both the shebang and the execute bit set, the latter granted once with change-mode plus x. Running it as a command is preferable, because it makes your script behave like any other command; drop it into a directory on your path and you can call it from anywhere.

There are a few common shebang variants worth recognising. Pointing straight at bash gives you guaranteed bash with all its features, which is what you will use almost all the time. Pointing at the plain s-h gives you a more portable posix shell, but without bash-only extras. And there is a popular form that runs env and then bash, which finds bash by searching your path, useful for scripts that should also work on a mac. Inside a script, command-line arguments arrive as numbered variables: dollar-zero is the script's own name, dollar-one the first argument, dollar-two the second, and so on, with dollar-at standing for all of them and dollar-hash for how many there are.
